{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488553"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:47:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:47:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"478"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/478"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.05,0.2,0.01,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"478"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50837"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/478"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"478"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36073"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"201"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2124"},{"type":"tags","id":"2267"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"2702"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1713"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1928"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14485"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43013"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50837"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old stonemason presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of worsening shortness of breath, dry cough, and reduced exercise tolerance. He has a medical history of asthma which is reasonably well controlled on as-needed salbutamol. He does not take any other regular medications. He has never smoked. He works as a stonemason. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is no clubbing of his fingers. Auscultation reveals scattered fine inspiratory crackles predominantly in his upper lung lobes. There is no wheeze. A chest X-ray demonstrates reticulo-nodular opacities more predominant in the upper zones of the lungs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High resolution CT chest","Lung biopsy","Pulmonary function tests","PET scan","Bronchoscopy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis relatively young, non-smoking man presents with progressive shortness of breath, dry cough, and reduced exercise tolerance. His occupation as a stonemason, along with the examination findings of fine inspiratory crackles and chest X-ray showing reticulo-nodular opacities, raises clinical suspicion of interstitial lung disease, particularly silicosis (a form of pneumoconiosis). However, he must be evaluated for other causes of interstitial lung disease as well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh resolution CT chest\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation and is considered the gold standard for evaluating interstitial lung disease. It provides detailed images of lung parenchyma, allowing for better characterization of the pattern and distribution of lung abnormalities. This information is crucial for narrowing down the differential diagnosis and guiding further management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary function tests\u003C/strong\u003E would likely show a restrictive pattern, which would add to the clinical suspicion of interstitial lung disease. However, they would not provide as much diagnostic information as the high resolution CT. While useful, they are typically performed in conjunction with imaging rather than as an alternative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E with bronchoalveolar lavage and/or transbronchial biopsy may be needed to diagnose specific types of interstitial lung disease, but it would not be performed before high resolution CT chest. The CT findings often guide the decision on whether bronchoscopy is necessary and which areas to target.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELung biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly surgical lung biopsy, is sometimes required for definitive diagnosis of certain interstitial lung diseases. However, it is an invasive procedure with associated risks and is typically considered only after less invasive investigations have been performed, including high resolution CT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPET scan\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely used in the initial evaluation of suspected interstitial lung disease. It may have a role in assessing for malignancy in patients with lung nodules or masses, but it is not the next appropriate step in this clinical scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, high resolution CT chest is the most appropriate next investigation for this patient with suspected interstitial lung disease. It will provide valuable information about the pattern and distribution of lung abnormalities, guiding further diagnostic steps and management decisions. The occupational history of stone masonry is particularly relevant here, as it raises the possibility of silicosis, a type of pneumoconiosis caused by inhalation of silica dust.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A high resolution CT is the investigation of choice for suspected interstitial lung disease.","Occupational history is crucial in evaluating patients with respiratory symptoms, particularly for conditions like silicosis.","Fine inspiratory crackles and reticulo-nodular opacities on chest X-ray are suggestive of interstitial lung disease."],"references":["Ward J, McDonald C. Interstitial lung disease: An approach to diagnosis and management. Australian family physician. 2010 Mar;39(3):106-10.","Semasinghe Bandaralage SP, Sriram KB. A young man with progressive worsening dyspnoea. Australian journal of general practice. 2018 Dec;47(12):856-8."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36073"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"478"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36073"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-17T23:04:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-17T23:05:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"478"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50837"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":nu